    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-01-29T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-01-29T13:00:00-05:00" n="519"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d519">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">394.31/1–2951: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bonsai</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-01-29T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >January 29, 1951—7 p. m</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4461. Torquay’s telegram 370, January 26, 1951 to Washington, repeated Paris 26,
                    January 26, 1951.<note n="1" xml:id="d519fn1">Not printed.</note> Embassy office
                    took occasion ask Wormser,<note n="2" xml:id="d519fn2">Olivier Wormser, <hi
                            rend="italic">Chef de Service</hi>, Economic Cooperation, in Economic
                        and Financial Affairs, French Ministry of Foreign Affairs.</note> in charge
                    multilateral affairs, <gloss target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> views re French
                    position Blankenstein tariff reduction proposal. Wormser confidentially
                    indicated that <gloss target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> was definitely opposed.
                    Embassy suggests that statement by Lecuyer<note n="3" xml:id="d519fn3">Ernest
                        Lecuyer, member of the French Delegation to the Torquay Conference.</note>
                    supporting further exploration Blankenstein proposal should be interpreted
                        accordingly.<note n="4" xml:id="d519fn4">Lecuyer’s statement had been
                        reported in telegram 370, January 26, not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent Department 4461, repeated information Torquay 16.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bonsal</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
